          "body": "The Elisha episode (13:14-19) is the chapter's literary and theological climax, even though it interrupts the political history. Joash's cry — 'My father, my father, the chariots of Israel and its horsemen!' (13:14) — is the same cry Elisha himself uttered when Elijah was taken up (2 Kings 2:12). The king knows what he is losing. He also knows that Israel's true military security is not in ten chariots but in the word of a prophet. What follows is one of Scripture's most searching enacted parables. Elisha lays his hands on the king's hands and commands him to shoot eastward (toward Aram). Then: take the arrows and strike the ground. The king strikes three times and stops. Elisha's anger is immediate and specific — 'You should have struck five or six times.' The king's failure was not disobedience; it was insufficiency. He did what was commanded but without the wholehearted intensity the moment required. The prophetic parable reveals a sobering principle: the scope of divinely promised blessing can be narrowed by the quality of the faith-response it receives. Joash's three strikes were real obedience. But three was less than the situation demanded, and the prophecy calibrated itself to what faith could hold."
