          "body": "Verse 21 is one of the strangest and most theologically potent verses in the historical books. A burial party, surprised by Moabite raiders, throws a corpse into the nearest available tomb — Elisha's. The moment the dead man's body touches Elisha's bones, he revives and stands on his feet. No invocation, no prayer, no Elisha present — just physical contact with the remains of a man whose entire ministry had been characterized by the life-giving power of the LORD. The miracle is not about the bones as relics (the narrator does not encourage pilgrimage to the tomb); it is about the God who authorized the ministry of Elisha and whose power is not exhausted when the instrument dies. This is the narrator's answer to the implied question raised by Elisha's death: does Israel now lose God's active power on its behalf? The answer is no — God raises the dead through a dead prophet. The miracle also functions as a small-scale enacted promise of what God can do for a nation that is itself dying. Israel is dust at threshing (13:7); but the God who raised a dead man through Elisha's bones can raise a nation."
