          "body": "Verse 23 is the theological hinge of the entire chapter and, arguably, of the entire section of 2 Kings from chapter 10 through 17. After narrating years of oppression under Hazael, the narrator pauses to give the divine rationale for why Israel still exists at all: 'the LORD was gracious to them and had compassion on them and turned to them because of His covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.' Three verbs of divine disposition — gracious (*chanan*), compassionate (*racham*), turned — and one ground: the Abrahamic covenant. The northern kings have given the narrator nothing else to work with. There is no sustained faithfulness, no covenant obedience, no repentance that matches the deliverance received. The only explanation for Israel's survival is God's own sworn commitment to the patriarchs, made before any of these kings existed, binding God to a people who have done almost nothing to honor it. This is not a narrative of divine passivity or indifference to sin — the chapter has already recorded judgment (13:3). It is a narrative of covenant-controlled mercy: God punishes, but He will not destroy, because He is bound by His own word to Abraham. The phrase 'until now' (13:23) is the chapter's most ominous note — it signals that this window of mercy will close, as 2 Kings 17 narrates in the Assyrian exile of 722 BC."
