        "excerpt": "Nevertheless they did not turn away from the sins of the house of Jeroboam... but walked in them; and the Asherah also remained standing in Samaria.",
        "body": "The opening six verses of 2 Kings 13 function as a compressed theological argument about the nature of Israel's relationship with God. The Deuteronomistic historian — the theological editor who shaped the books of Kings through the lens of Deuteronomy's covenant blessings and curses — follows a fixed evaluative pattern: accession notice, moral verdict, consequence, and either partial recovery or unrelieved decline. Here the pattern is complete, and its completion is precisely what indicts.\n\nJehoahaz's prayer in verse 4 is remarkable in its apparent sincerity — the Hebrew *chalah eth paneh YHWH* ('entreated the favor of the LORD') is a strong formula of supplication, used of Moses (Exodus 32:11) and Hezekiah (2 Chronicles 30:18). The LORD's response is genuine: He hears, He sees the oppression, He provides a deliverer (13:5). But verse 6 follows with the adversative *akh* ('nevertheless') — a small word that carries enormous theological weight. The deliverance was real. The return to normal life was real. And the sin was still real, unchanged, still standing in stone in the form of the Asherah pole in Samaria.\n\nWhat the text describes is the spiritual danger of extracting God's rescue from the repentance that should accompany it. Jehoahaz prayed in the language of covenant dependence but walked in the pattern of Jeroboam. This is not hypocrisy in the malicious sense; it is the more common and more dangerous failure of treating crisis prayer as sufficient while leaving the structural sin untouched. The Asherah pole standing in Samaria after the deliverance is the chapter's opening irony: God answered the prayer while the pole He most wanted removed was still erect.\n\nChuck Swindoll, commenting on the northern kings' recidivism, observes that God's mercy in 13:5 is not conditioned on Israel deserving it — but neither is it indifferent to what Israel does with it. The 'deliverer' of verse 5 is anonymous: the narrator does not name him because the point is not the human instrument but the divine provision. Most scholars (following the chronological logic of 2 Kings 14:27) identify the deliverer as Jeroboam II, whose expansion of Israel's borders reversed the Aramean losses. The anonymity in chapter 13 is deliberate — it keeps the theological focus on the LORD rather than the man.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Akh* (nevertheless, v.6) is the chapter's sharpest adversative. *Chalah eth paneh* (entreated the favor, v.4) — literally 'made smooth/soft the face of the LORD' — a strong formula of petition. *Sur* (turn away, v.6) — the repentance-word Israel did not perform; the same verb used in covenant-keeping contexts throughout Deuteronomy. The Asherah (*asherah*, v.6) was a wooden pole or stylized tree representing the Canaanite fertility goddess — its presence in Samaria signals the syncretism that the LORD had forbidden since Sinai."
